	<h2 id="introduction-and-scope" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Introduction and scope</h2>
	<p>
		Low-resource optimisation (LRO) is often framed primarily in the context of web delivery: focusing on performance,
		accessibility, and usability under constrained network and device conditions. While this perspective is essential,
		it captures only one part of a broader challenge.
	</p>
	<p>
		EMBL-EBI <strong>operates as part of a global biodata infrastructure</strong> rather than as a provider of standalone websites.
		Users engage with its services through a combination of interfaces and workflows, including interactive web tools,
		bulk data access, programmatic APIs, analysis pipelines, and data submission systems. As a result, limitations
		affecting users frequently extend beyond the web layer.
	</p>
	<p>
		This document provides a high-level definition and scope of low-resource settings across this wider service
		landscape. It complements web-focused optimisation guidance by articulating the broader set of constraints that
		shape how users access, analyse, submit, and reuse data.
	</p>
	<p>
		Within this context, a low-resource setting is understood as an environment in which one or more constraints
		significantly limit a user's ability to interact effectively with biodata services (for example: genomics)
		across the full lifecycle: from discovery and access to computation, submission, and reuse.
	</p>
	<p>
		These <strong>constraints are inherently multi-dimensional</strong>, spanning infrastructure, data scale, compute capacity,
		storage, device capability, and institutional support. The sections that follow outline these dimensions and
		their implications for service design and delivery beyond the web interface.
	</p>

	<h2 id="connectivity-and-reliability" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Connectivity and Reliability</h2>
	<p>
		Connectivity constraints extend beyond bandwidth to include stability, latency, and cost.
	</p>
	<p>
		Workflows supported by EMBL-EBI are often sensitive to unreliable networks, particularly where they involve
		large data transfers, long-running processes, or stateful interactions. For example, in genomics, large
		transfers (for example, FASTA, BAM, VCF) may fail, job submissions can time out, and APIs become unreliable
		under intermittent connectivity. Many services assume persistent connections that are not always available.
	</p>
	<p>
		In practice, users may have nominal internet access but still experience low-resource conditions due to:
	</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Intermittent or unstable connectivity (high latency, packet loss)</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Unreliable access to electricity</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Institutional constraints, such as data caps or costly bandwidth</li>
	</ul>
	<p>
		These factors directly impact the reliability of long-running or stateful operations.
	</p>

	<h2 id="data-scale-and-transfer-burden" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Data Scale and Transfer Burden</h2>
	<p>
		Biodata resources are data-intensive, often involving gigabytes to terabytes per project, including reference
		genomes, variation datasets, and annotation resources.
	</p>
	<p>
		Users in constrained environments may struggle to:
	</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Download large datasets</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Maintain stable, long-lived connections</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Upload data for submission workflows</li>
	</ul>
	<p>
		Even where web interfaces are optimised, the data remains large. This may lead to:
	</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Reliance on partial or pre-filtered datasets</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Inability to maintain local mirrors</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Reduced reproducibility of analyses</li>
	</ul>
	<p>
		This highlights the tension between open data availability and practical usability.
	</p>

	<h2 id="compute-and-local-capacity" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Compute and Local Capacity</h2>
	<p>
		Effective use of biodata resources (for example, genomics) typically requires downstream compute capability
		beyond simple browsing.
	</p>
	<p>
		Common use cases include running analysis pipelines, indexing datasets, or hosting local reference data.
		In low-resource environments, users may have:
	</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">No access to HPC or cloud computing</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Only consumer-grade hardware</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Limited CPU, memory, or GPU capability</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Restricted ability to run containerised workflows</li>
	</ul>
	<p>
		In many cases, the limiting factor is not access to the service but the ability to use the data meaningfully.
	</p>

	<h2 id="storage-and-infrastructure-constraints" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Storage and Infrastructure Constraints</h2>
	<p>
		Biodata resource workflows depend on significant storage for raw data, intermediate files, and outputs.
	</p>
	<p>
		Users may face:
	</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Limited local or institutional storage</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Shared infrastructure with restricted quotas</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Lack of reliable backup</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Filesystem performance limitations</li>
	</ul>
	<p>
		This constrains the ability to store reference datasets, cache results, or maintain reproducible workflows,
		and challenges the assumption that users can simply "download and run locally".
	</p>

	<h2 id="device-and-software-capability" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Device and Software Capability</h2>
	<p>
		Advanced biodata (for example, genomics) interfaces, particularly genome browsers and visualisation tools,
		can be resource-intensive.
	</p>
	<p>
		Users may rely on:
	</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Low-spec or outdated institutional machines</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Shared lab environments with restricted permissions</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Tablets or mobile devices in the field or in teaching contexts</li>
	</ul>
	<p>
		These constraints can limit usability, especially for interactive or multi-track visualisation,
		and may restrict access to key functionality.
	</p>

	<h2 id="participation-barriers" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Participation Barriers (Submission and Contribution)</h2>
	<p>
		Low-resource constraints affect not only data access but also participation in data sharing.
	</p>
	<p>
		Submitting data to archives (for example, ENA, EVA) typically requires:
	</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Reliable upstream bandwidth</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Preparation of complex metadata</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Validation steps requiring computation and iteration</li>
	</ul>
	<p>
		Failures are costly in terms of time and effort, and may discourage participation. Geographic distance from
		infrastructure can also introduce higher latency and reduced reliability.
	</p>
	<p>
		These factors can limit equitable participation in global biodata initiatives.
	</p>

	<h2 id="skills-and-institutional-support" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Skills and Institutional Support</h2>
	<p>
		Technical infrastructure alone is insufficient without the skills and support needed to use it effectively.
	</p>
	<p>
		Barriers may include:
	</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Limited access to bioinformatics training</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Lack of institutional IT or research support</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Difficulty installing or maintaining tools</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Language diversity and limited localisation</li>
	</ul>
	<p>
		Low-resource settings, therefore, reflect not only technical constraints but also limitations in capacity and support.
	</p>

	<h2 id="economic-and-systemic-constraints" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Economic and Systemic Constraints</h2>
	<p>
		Many of the above challenges are underpinned by broader economic and systemic factors, including:
	</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Limited funding for infrastructure and equipment</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">High relative cost of connectivity and compute</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Procurement constraints</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Geopolitical factors affecting access to services or technologies</li>
	</ul>
	<p>
		These influence both individual users and institutions over time.
	</p>

	<h2 id="summary" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Summary</h2>
	<p>
		Low-resource settings in biodata (for example, genomics) are not defined by a single limitation, but by the
		interaction of multiple constraints across the service lifecycle. Connectivity, data scale, compute capacity,
		storage, device capability, and institutional support all play a role in determining whether a user can
		effectively access and use EMBL-EBI services.
	</p>
	<p>
		This broader perspective highlights that, in many cases, barriers arise not at the point of web access,
		but in downstream activities such as data transfer, local analysis, or data submission.
		As such, <strong>optimising web interfaces alone is necessary but not sufficient</strong> to address the full spectrum of challenges.
	</p>
	<p>
		Understanding <strong>low-resource settings as a multi-dimensional problem</strong> enables a more realistic interpretation
		of user constraints and helps identify where interventions may have the greatest impact across the ecosystem.
	</p>
	<p>
		At the same time, not all aspects of low-resource environments are directly addressable through service design.
		This document therefore serves primarily as a framing layer: it defines the broader context within which low-resource
		optimisation operates and informs where targeted, practical improvements including but not limited to web optimisation
		can be prioritised.
	</p>
	<p>
		In this way, it complements existing guidance focused on web services, while providing a foundation for future work
		that considers low-resource optimisation across the full biodata service landscape.
	</p>

